Step 1 – Install Ollama (Required)
Go to ollama.com/download/windows

Download and run the installer.

After installation, Ollama will start automatically (you’ll see its icon in the system tray).

Optional but recommended:
Open a terminal and pull a model (e.g., llama3.2:3b):

bash
ollama pull llama3.2:3b
You can also use mistral, phi3, llama3.1:8b, etc.

If Ollama is running, you’ll see Ollama is running when you open http://localhost:11434 in a browser.

📦 Step 2 – Run the Gyani Baba Installer
Double‑click GyaniBaba_Setup.exe.

Windows may show a “Windows protected your PC” warning – click “More info” and “Run anyway” (since you built it).

Follow the installer:

Choose installation folder (default: C:\Program Files\Gyani Baba).

Choose Start Menu folder.

Optionally check “Create a desktop shortcut”.

Click Install.

After completion, leave the “Launch Gyani Baba” checkbox checked or run the app manually.

⚙️ Step 3 – First Run
The first time the app starts:

It creates a config.json file (with default settings) in its installation folder.

It creates a gyani_workspace\ folder and data\ folder (for database).

It tries to connect to Ollama at http://localhost:11434.

If Ollama is running and the model you set in config.json is available, everything works.

🔧 Step 4 – Configure (If Needed)
The app uses config.json. You can edit it with Notepad to:

Change the LLM endpoint (e.g., to a remote server).

Change the model name.

Set email/calendar credentials (optional).

Default location:
C:\Program Files\Gyani Baba\config.json

🚀 Step 5 – Run Gyani Baba
From Start Menu: Start → Gyani Baba → Gyani Baba

From Desktop: double‑click the shortcut.

From installation folder: double‑click GyaniBaba.exe.

The GUI will appear – start chatting!

